🚀 Day 06 – Debugging Strings & Data Cleaning Issues in Python
Python Debugging Lab (14-Day Series)

Today I focused on one of the most underrated debugging areas:

👉 String handling & data cleaning bugs

In real-world data analytics, most errors don’t come from algorithms — they come from messy strings.

🔍 Topics Covered

Case sensitivity issues

Hidden whitespace bugs

Incorrect string comparisons

.strip(), .lower() usage

Index errors in strings

Safe string parsing

💡 Key Learning #1 – Case Sensitivity Bug
name = "Devansh"

if name == "devansh":
    print("Match")

This condition fails.

Why?

Python string comparison is case-sensitive.

Safer approach:

if name.lower() == "devansh":
    print("Match")
💡 Key Learning #2 – Hidden Whitespace Bug
email = "user@gmail.com "

if email == "user@gmail.com":
    print("Valid")

This fails because of trailing space.

Correct approach:

email = email.strip()

Always clean strings before comparison.

💡 Key Learning #3 – IndexError in Strings
s = "Python"
print(s[6])

This crashes:

IndexError: string index out of range

Valid indexes:

0 → P
1 → y
2 → t
3 → h
4 → o
5 → n

Last index is len(s) - 1.

💡 Key Learning #4 – Splitting Data Safely
data = "100,200,300"
values = data.split(",")

print(values)

Output:
['100', '200', '300']

Always remember:

After splitting → values are strings, not integers.

Convert safely:

values = [int(v) for v in values]
🎯 Why This Matters

String bugs can:

Break dataset filtering

Cause incorrect joins

Produce wrong aggregations

Fail production APIs

In Data Analytics & Data Engineering, string cleaning is debugging.
